# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wsl-subsystem
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] In software engineering, a **compatibility layer** is an interface that allows binaries for a legacy or foreign system to run on a host system.
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] This translates system calls for the foreign system into native system calls for the host system.
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] With some libraries for the foreign system, this will often be sufficient to run foreign binaries on the host system.
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] A hardware compatibility layer consists of tools that allow hardware emulation.
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] A compatibility layer avoids both the complexity and the speed penalty of full hardware emulation.
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] Some programs may even run faster than the original, *e.g.* some Linux applications running on FreeBSD's Linux compatibility layer may perform better than the same applications on Red Hat Linux.
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] Benchmarks are occasionally run on Wine to compare it to Windows NT-based operating systems.
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] Even on similar systems, the details of implementing a compatibility layer can be quite intricate and troublesome; a good example is the IRIX binary compatibility layer in the MIPS architecture version of NetBSD.
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] A compatibility layer requires the host system's CPU to be (upwardly) compatible to that of the foreign system.
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] For example, a Microsoft Windows compatibility layer is not possible on PowerPC hardware because Windows requires an x86 CPU.
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] Hardware compatibility layers involve tools that allow hardware emulation.
[src:wsl-subsystem/compatibility-layer] Some hardware compatibility layers involve breakout boxes because breakout boxes can provide compatibility for certain computer buses that are otherwise incompatible with the machine.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] The terminal emulator mintty is the default command-line interface provided to interact with the environment.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] The Cygwin installation directory layout mimics the root file system of Unix-like systems, with directories such as `/bin`, `/home`, `/etc`, `/usr`, and `/var`.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin is released under the GNU Lesser General Public License version 3.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] It was originally developed by Cygnus Solutions, which was later acquired by Red Hat (now part of IBM), to port the GNU toolchain to Win32, including the GNU Compiler Suite.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Rather than rewrite the tools to use the Win32 runtime environment, Cygwin implemented a POSIX-compatible environment in the form of a DLL.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] The brand motto is "*Get that Linux feeling – on Windows*", although Cygwin doesn't have Linux in it.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin began in 1995 as a project of Steve Chamberlain, a Cygnus engineer who observed that Windows NT and 95 used COFF as their object file format, and that GNU already included support for x86 and COFF, and the C library newlib.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] He thought that it would be possible to retarget GCC and produce a cross compiler generating executables that could run on Windows.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Chamberlain bootstrapped the compiler on a Windows system, to emulate Unix to let the GNU configure shell script run.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Initially, Cygwin was called *Cygwin32*.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] When Microsoft registered the trademark Win32, the "32" was dropped to simply become *Cygwin*.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] In 1999, Cygnus offered Cygwin 1.0 as a commercial product.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Subsequent versions have not been released, instead relying on continued open source releases.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Geoffrey Noer was the project lead from 1996 to 1999.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Christopher Faylor was lead from 1999 to 2004; he left Red Hat and became co-lead with Corinna Vinschen.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Corinna Vinschen has been the project lead from mid-2014 to date (as of September, 2024).
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] From June 23, 2016, the Cygwin library version 2.5.2 was licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL) version 3.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin is provided in two versions: the full 64-bit version and a stripped-down 32-bit version, whose final version was released in 2022.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin consists of a library that implements the POSIX system call API in terms of Windows system calls to enable the running of a large number of application programs equivalent to those on Unix systems, and a GNU development toolchain (including GCC and GDB).
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Programmers have ported the X Window System, K Desktop Environment 3, GNOME, Apache, and TeX.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin permits installing inetd, syslogd, sshd, Apache, and other daemons as standard Windows services.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin programs have full access to the Windows API and other Windows libraries.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin programs are installed by running Cygwin's "setup" program, which downloads them from repositories on the Internet.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] The Cygwin API library is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License version 3 (or later), with an exception to allow linking to any free and open-source software whose license conforms to the Open Source Definition.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] A collection of software tools and applications that provide a Unix-like look and feel.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin supports POSIX symbolic links, representing them as plain-text files with the system attribute set.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin 1.5 represented them as Windows Explorer shortcuts, but this was changed for reasons of performance and POSIX correctness.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin also recognises NTFS junction points and symbolic links and treats them as POSIX symbolic links, but it does not create them.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] The POSIX API for handling access control lists (ACLs) is supported.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] A Cygwin-specific version of the Unix `mount` command allows mounting Windows paths as "filesystems" in the Unix file space.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Initial mount points can be configured in `/etc/fstab`, which has a format very similar to Unix systems, except that Windows paths appear in place of devices.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Filesystems can be mounted in binary mode (by default), or in text mode, which enables automatic conversion between LF and CRLF endings (which only affects programs that open files without explicitly specifying text or binary mode).
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin 1.7 introduced comprehensive support for POSIX locales, and the UTF-8 Unicode encoding became the default.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] The fork system call for duplicating a process is fully implemented, but the copy-on-write optimization strategy could not be used.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin's default user interface is the bash shell running in the mintty terminal emulator.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] The DLL also implements pseudo terminal (pty) devices, and Cygwin ships with a number of terminal emulators that are based on them, including rxvt/urxvt and xterm.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] The version of GCC that comes with Cygwin has various extensions for creating Windows DLLs, such as specifying whether a program is a windowing or console-mode program.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Support for compiling programs that do not require the POSIX compatibility layer provided by the Cygwin DLL used to be included in the default GCC, but as of 2014, it is provided by cross-compilers contributed by the MinGW-w64 project.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Cygwin's base package selection is approximately 100MB, containing the bash (interactive user) and dash (installation) shells and the core file and text manipulation utilities.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Additional packages are available as optional installs from within the Cygwin "setup" program and package manager ("setup-x86_64.exe" – 64 bit).
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] The Cygwin Ports project provided additional packages that were not available in the Cygwin distribution itself.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Examples included GNOME, K Desktop Environment 3, MySQL database, and the PHP scripting language.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] Most ports have been adopted by volunteer maintainers as Cygwin packages, and Cygwin Ports are no longer maintained.
[src:wsl-subsystem/cygwin] The Cygwin/X project allows graphical Unix programs to display their user interfaces on the Windows desktop for both local and remote programs.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Codenamed **Viridian** and briefly known before its release as **Windows Server Virtualization**, a beta version was shipped with certain x86-64 editions of Windows Server 2008.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] The finalized version was released on June 26, 2008 and was delivered through Windows Update.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V has since been released with every version of Windows Server starting with version 2012, superseding Microsoft Virtual Server, and starting with Windows 8, Hyper-V has been the hardware virtualization component for personal computers, superseding Windows Virtual PC.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V Server: It is a freeware edition of Windows Server with limited functionality and Hyper-V component.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V Server 2008 was released on October 1, 2008.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] It consists of Windows Server 2008 Server Core and Hyper-V role; other Windows Server 2008 roles are disabled, and there are limited Windows services.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V Server 2008 is limited to a command-line interface used to configure the host OS, physical hardware, and software.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] A menu driven command line interface (CLI) and some freely downloadable script files simplify configuration.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] In addition, Hyper-V Server supports remote access via Remote Desktop Connection.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] However, administration and configuration of the host OS and the guest virtual machines is generally done over the network, using either Microsoft Management Consoles on another Windows computer or System Center Virtual Machine Manager.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] This allows much easier "point and click" configuration, and monitoring of the Hyper-V Server.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V Server 2008 R2 (an edition of Windows Server 2008 R2) was made available in September 2009 and includes Windows PowerShell v2 for greater CLI control.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Remote access to Hyper-V Server requires CLI configuration of network interfaces and Windows Firewall.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Also using a Windows Vista PC to administer Hyper-V Server 2008 R2 is not fully supported.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Microsoft ended mainstream support of the free version of Hyper-V Server 2019 on January 9, 2024 and extended support will end on January 9, 2029.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V Server 2019 will be the last version of the free, standalone product.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V is still available as a role in Windows Server 2022 and will be supported as long as that operating system is, currently scheduled for end of extended support on October 14, 2031.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V implements isolation of virtual machines in terms of a *partition*.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] A partition is a logical unit of isolation, supported by the hypervisor, in which each guest operating system executes.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] There must be at least one *parent partition* in a hypervisor instance, running a supported version of Windows.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] The parent partition creates *child partitions* which host the guest OSs.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] The Virtualization Service Provider and Virtual Machine Management Service runs in the parent partition and provide support for child partition.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] A parent partition creates child partitions using the *hypercall* API, which is the application programming interface exposed by Hyper-V.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] A child partition does not have access to the physical processor, nor does it handle its real interrupts.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Instead, it has a virtual view of the processor and runs in *Guest Virtual Address*, which, depending on the configuration of the hypervisor, might not necessarily be the entire virtual address space.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Depending on VM configuration, Hyper-V may expose only a subset of the processors to each partition.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] The hypervisor handles the interrupts to the processor, and redirects them to the respective partition using a logical *Synthetic Interrupt Controller* (SynIC).
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V can hardware accelerate the address translation of Guest Virtual Address-spaces by using second level address translation provided by the CPU, referred to as EPT on Intel and RVI (formerly NPT) on AMD.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Child partitions do not have direct access to hardware resources, but instead have a virtual view of the resources, in terms of *virtual devices*.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Any request to the virtual devices is redirected via the *VMBus* to the devices in the parent partition, which will manage the requests.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] The VMBus is a logical channel which enables inter-partition communication.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] The response is also redirected via the VMBus.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] If the devices in the parent partition are also virtual devices, it will be redirected further until it reaches the parent partition, where it will gain access to the physical devices.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Parent partitions run a *Virtualization Service Provider* (VSP), which connects to the VMBus and handles device access requests from child partitions.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Child partition virtual devices internally run a *Virtualization Service Client* (VSC), which redirect the request to VSPs in the parent partition via the VMBus.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] This entire process is transparent to the guest OS.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Virtual devices can also take advantage of a Windows Server Virtualization feature, named *Enlightened I/O*, for storage, networking and graphics subsystems, among others.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Enlightened I/O is a specialized virtualization-aware implementation of high level communication protocols, like SCSI, that allows bypassing any device emulation layer and takes advantage of VMBus directly.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] This makes the communication more efficient, but requires the guest OS to support Enlightened I/O.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] The Hyper-V role is only available in the x86-64 variants of Standard, Enterprise and Datacenter editions of Windows Server 2008 and later, as well as the Pro, Enterprise and Education editions of Windows 8 and later.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] On Windows Server, it can be installed regardless of whether the installation is a full or core installation.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] In addition, Hyper-V can be made available as part of the Hyper-V Server operating system, which is a freeware edition of Windows Server.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Either way, the host computer needs the following.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] There is also a maximum for the number of concurrently active virtual machines.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] The following table lists supported guest operating systems on Windows Server 2008 R2 SP1.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Web edition does not have an x64 version.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Fedora 8 or 9 are unsupported; however, they have been reported to run.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Third-party support for FreeBSD 8.2 and later guests is provided by a partnership between NetApp and Citrix.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] This includes both emulated and paravirtualized modes of operation, as well as several HyperV integration services.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Non-"enlightened" operating systems will run with emulated I/O; however, *integration components* (which include the VSC drivers) are available for Windows Server 2003 SP2, Windows Vista SP1 and Linux to achieve better performance.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] On July 20, 2009, Microsoft submitted Hyper-V drivers for inclusion in the Linux kernel under the terms of the GPL.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Microsoft was required to submit the code when it was discovered that they had incorporated a Hyper-V network driver with GPL-licensed components statically linked to closed-source binaries.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Kernels beginning with 2.6.32 may include inbuilt Hyper-V paravirtualization support which improves the performance of virtual Linux guest systems in a Windows host environment.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V provides basic virtualization support for Linux guests out of the box.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Paravirtualization support requires installing the Linux Integration Components or Satori InputVSC drivers.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Xen-enabled Linux guest distributions may also be paravirtualized in Hyper-V.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] As of 2013 Microsoft officially supported only SUSE Linux Enterprise Server 10 SP1/SP2 (x86 and x64) in this manner, though any Xen-enabled Linux should be able to run.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] In February 2008, Red Hat and Microsoft signed a virtualization pact for hypervisor interoperability with their respective server operating systems, to enable Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5 to be officially supported on Hyper-V.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Minimum supported version of CentOS is 6.0.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Minimum supported version of Red Hat Enterprise Linux is 5.7.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Maximum number of supported CPUs for Windows Server and Linux operating systems is increased from four to 64.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V on Windows Server 2012 R2 added the Generation 2 VM.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V, like Microsoft Virtual Server and Windows Virtual PC, saves each guest OS to a single virtual hard disk file.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] It supports the older .vhd format, as well as the newer .vhdx.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Older .vhd files from Virtual Server 2005, Virtual PC 2004 and Virtual PC 2007 can be copied and used in Hyper-V, but any old virtual machine integration software (equivalents of Hyper-V Integration Services) must be removed from the virtual machine.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] After the migrated guest OS is configured and started using Hyper-V, the guest OS will detect changes to the (virtual) hardware.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Installing "Hyper-V Integration Services" installs five services to improve performance, at the same time adding the new guest video and network card drivers.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V does not virtualize audio hardware.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Before Windows 8.1 and Windows Server 2012 R2, it was possible to work around this issue by connecting to the virtual machine with Remote Desktop Connection over a network connection and use its audio redirection feature.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Windows 8.1 and Windows Server 2012 R2 add the enhanced session mode which provides redirection without a network connection.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Optical drives virtualized in the guest VM are read-only.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Officially Hyper-V does not support the host/root operating system's optical drives to pass-through in guest VMs.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] As a result, burning to discs, audio CDs, video CD/DVD-Video playback are not supported; however, a workaround exists using the iSCSI protocol.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Setting up an iSCSI target on the host machine with the optical drive can then be talked to by the standard Microsoft iSCSI initiator.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Microsoft produces their own iSCSI Target software or alternative third party products can be used.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V uses the VT-x on Intel or AMD-V on AMD x86 virtualization.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Since Hyper-V is a native hypervisor, as long as it is installed, third-party software cannot use VT-x or AMD-V.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] For instance, the Intel HAXM Android device emulator (used by Android Studio or Microsoft Visual Studio) cannot run while Hyper-V is installed.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V is a native hypervisor, and enabling Hyper-V on host Windows operating system downloads and installs additional components to the operating system.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Enabling Hyper-V may cause performance degradation on hosts, even if no Hyper-V virtual machine is running.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Hyper-V is also available in x64 SKUs of Windows 8, 8.1, 10 Pro, Enterprise, Education.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] Windows Server 2012 introduced many new features in Hyper-V.
[src:wsl-subsystem/hyper-v] With Windows Server 2012 R2 Microsoft introduced another set of new features.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The operating system introduced a redesigned Windows shell influenced by elements of the canceled Windows 10X project, including a centered Start menu, a separate "Widgets" panel replacing live tiles, and new window management features.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] It also incorporates gaming technologies from the Xbox Series X and Series S, such as Auto HDR and DirectStorage on supported hardware.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The Chromium-based Microsoft Edge remains the default web browser, replacing Internet Explorer, while Microsoft Teams is integrated into the interface.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Microsoft also expanded support for third-party applications in the Microsoft Store, including limited compatibility with Android apps through a partnership with the Amazon Appstore.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 introduced significantly higher system requirements than typical operating system upgrades, which Microsoft attributed to security considerations.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The operating system requires features such as UEFI, Secure Boot, and Trusted Platform Module (TPM) version 2.0.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Official support is limited to devices with an eighth-generation Intel Core or newer processor, a second-generation AMD Ryzen or newer processor, or a Qualcomm Snapdragon 850 or later system-on-chip.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] These restrictions exclude a substantial number of systems, prompting criticism from users and media.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] While installation on unsupported hardware is technically possible, Microsoft does not guarantee access to updates or support.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] It is the first version of Windows without a 32-bit build, running only on x86-64 and ARM64 architectures; despite this, it is still able to run 32-bit applications through the WoW64 subsystem, which 64-bit versions of Windows have been using since Windows XP.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 received mixed reviews upon its release.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Prelaunch discussion focused on its increased hardware requirements, with debate over whether these changes were primarily motivated by security improvements or to encourage users to purchase newer devices.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The operating system was generally praised for its updated visual design, improved window management, and enhanced security features.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] However, critics pointed to changes in the user interface, such as limitations on taskbar customization and difficulties in changing default applications, as steps back from Windows 10.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In June 2025, Windows 11 surpassed Windows 10 as the most installed version of Windows worldwide.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] As of May 2026, Windows 11 is the most used version of Windows, accounting for 72% of the worldwide market share, while its predecessor Windows 10 holds 26%, and Windows 7 holds 1%.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 is the most-used traditional PC operating system, with a 38% share of users.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] At the 2015 Ignite conference, Microsoft employee Jerry Nixon stated that Windows 10 would be the "last version of Windows".
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The operating system was considered to be a service, with new builds and updates to be released over time.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] *PC World* argued that the widely reported comment was, however, taken out of context, noting that the official event transcript marks it only as a segue rather than a core part of the talk.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] It argues that Nixon was referring to the fact that he could talk freely at the event because 10 was the last version in current development.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In October 2019, Microsoft announced "Windows 10X", a future edition of Windows 10 designed exclusively for dual-touchscreen devices such as the then-upcoming Surface Neo.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] It featured a modified user interface designed around context-sensitive "postures" for different screen configurations and usage scenarios, and changes such as a centered taskbar and updated Start menu without Windows 10's "live tiles".
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Legacy Windows applications would also be required to run in "containers" to ensure performance and power optimization.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Microsoft stated that it planned to release Windows 10X devices by the end of 2020.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In October 2020, reports emerged that Microsoft was working on a user interface refresh for Windows 10 codenamed "Sun Valley", scheduled to be included in a late-2021 feature update codenamed "Cobalt".
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Internal documentation stated that the aim for "Sun Valley" was to "reinvigorat[e]" the Windows user interface and make it more "fluid", with a more consistent application of WinUI, while reports suggested Microsoft planned to adapt UI elements seen in Windows 10X.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In January 2021, it was reported that a job listing referring to a "sweeping visual rejuvenation of Windows" had been posted by Microsoft.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] On May 18, 2021, Head of Windows Servicing and Delivery John Cable stated that Windows 10X had been canceled and that Microsoft would be "accelerating the integration of key foundational 10X technology into other parts of Windows and products at the company".
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] At the Microsoft Build 2021 developer conference, CEO and chairman Satya Nadella teased about the existence of the next generation of Windows during his keynote speech.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] According to Nadella, he had been self-hosting it for several months.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] He also teased that an official announcement would come very soon.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Just a week after Nadella's keynote, Microsoft started sending invitations for a dedicated Windows media event at 11:00 a.m.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Microsoft also posted an 11-minute video of Windows start-up sounds to YouTube on June 10, 2021, with many people speculating both the time of the Microsoft event and the duration of the Windows start-up sound video to be a reference to the name of the operating system as Windows 11.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] On June 24, 2021, Windows 11 was officially announced at a virtual event hosted by Chief Product Officer Panos Panay.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] According to Nadella, Windows 11 is "a re-imagining of the operating system".
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Further details for developers such as updates to the Microsoft Store, the new Windows App SDK (code-named "Project Reunion"), new Fluent Design guidelines, and more were discussed during another developer-focused event on the same day.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The Windows 11 name was accidentally released in an official Microsoft support document in June 2021.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Leaked images of a purported beta build of Windows 11's desktop surfaced online later on June 15, 2021, which were followed by a leak of the aforementioned build on the same day.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The screenshots and leaked build show an interface resembling that of the canceled Windows 10X, alongside a redesigned out-of-box experience (OOBE) and Windows 11 branding.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Microsoft would later confirm the authenticity of the leaked beta, with Panay stating that it was an "early weird build".
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] At the June 24 media event, Microsoft also announced that Windows 11 would be released in "Holiday 2021".
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Its release will be accompanied by a free upgrade for compatible Windows 10 devices through Windows Update.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] On June 28, Microsoft announced the release of the first preview build and SDK of Windows 11 to Windows Insiders.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] On August 31, 2021, Microsoft announced that Windows 11 was to be released on October 5, 2021.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The release would be phased, with newer eligible devices to be offered the upgrade first.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The first television commercial for Windows 11 premiered during the 2021 NFL Kickoff Game on September 9, 2021; it was intended to showcase a "feeling of immersion and fluidity", with imagery of operating system features and Xbox Game Studios' *Halo Infinite*.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Other promotional campaigns on release day included the Burj Khalifa in Dubai being illuminated with imagery of the Windows 11 logo and default "Bloom" wallpaper (created by Barcelona-based art studio Six N.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Five), and Mikey Likes It ice cream parlors in New York City distributing free cups of "Bloomberry" ice cream.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] New installations of Windows 10 on eligible hardware may present an option to upgrade during the OOBE.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Retail copies of Windows 11 (consisting of a license key and USB flash drive) were released on May 9, 2022, and digital licenses became available via Microsoft Store on July 28, 2022.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] On September 20, 2023, around two years after the release date of Windows 11, Microsoft announced that users would no longer be able to use Windows 7 or Windows 8/8.1 product keys to activate Windows 10/11.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] As of 2024, however, some reports indicate that they still work, under certain conditions.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11, the first major Windows release since 2015, builds upon its predecessor by revamping the user interface to follow Microsoft's new Fluent Design guidelines.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The redesign, which focuses on ease of use and flexibility, comes alongside new productivity and social features and updates to security and accessibility, addressing some of the deficiencies of Windows 10.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The Microsoft Store, which serves as a unified storefront for apps and other content, is also redesigned in Windows 11.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Microsoft now allows developers to distribute Win32, progressive web applications, and other packaging technologies in the Microsoft Store, alongside Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Microsoft also announced plans to allow third-party application stores (such as Epic Games Store) to distribute their clients on Microsoft Store.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 supports x86-64 software emulation on ARM-based platforms.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The collaboration platform Microsoft Teams is integrated into the Windows 11 user interface, and is accessible via the taskbar.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Skype will no longer be bundled with the OS by default.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In early 2023, the Phone Link app gained limited support for iMessage.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Microsoft claims performance improvements such as smaller update sizes, faster web browsing in "any browser", faster wake time from sleep mode, and faster Windows Hello authentication.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 ships with the Chromium-based Microsoft Edge web browser (for compatibility with Google Chrome web browser), and does not include or support Internet Explorer.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Its rendering engine MSHTML (Trident) is still included with the operating system for backwards compatibility reasons, and Edge can be configured with Group Policy to render whitelisted websites in "IE Mode" (which still uses IE's rendering engine MSHTML, instead of Blink layout engine).
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 is the first version of Windows since the original retail release of Windows 95 to not ship with Internet Explorer.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] To comply with the Digital Markets Act, Microsoft is allowing users in the European Economic Area to remove the Microsoft Edge browser, Microsoft Bing search engine, and advertisements to comply with users' interests.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The updated Xbox app, along with the Auto HDR and DirectStorage technologies introduced by the Xbox Series X and Series S, were integrated into Windows 11; the latter requiring a graphics card supporting DirectX 12 and an NVMe solid-state drive.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] A redesigned user interface is present frequently throughout the operating system, building upon the Fluent Design System; translucency, shadows, a new color palette, and a rounded geometry are prevalent throughout the UI.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] A prevalent aspect of the design is an appearance known as "Mica", described as an "opaque, dynamic material that incorporates theme and desktop wallpaper to paint the background of long-lived windows such as apps and settings".
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Much of the interface and start menu takes heavy inspiration from the now-canceled Windows 10X.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The Segoe UI font used since Windows Vista has been updated to a variable version, improving its ability to scale between different display resolutions.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The taskbar's buttons are center-aligned by default, and it is permanently pinned to the bottom edge of the screen; it cannot be moved to the top, left, or right edges of the screen as in previous versions of Windows without manual changes to the registry.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The notifications sidebar is now accessed by clicking the date and time, with other Quick Actions toggles, as well as volume, brightness, and media playback controls, moved to a new settings pop-up displayed by clicking on the system tray.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The "Widgets" button on the taskbar displays a panel with Microsoft Start, a news aggregator with personalized stories and content (expanding upon the "news and interests" panel introduced in later builds of Windows 10).
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Microsoft Teams is similarly integrated with the taskbar, with a pop-up showing a list of recent conversations.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The Start menu has been significantly redesigned, replacing the "live tiles" used by Windows 8.x and 10 with a grid of "pinned" applications, and a list of recent applications and documents.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] File Explorer was updated to replace its ribbon toolbar with a more traditional toolbar, while its context menus have been redesigned to move some tasks (such as copy and paste) to a toolbar along the top of the menu, and hide other operations under an overflow menu.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Task View, a feature introduced in Windows 10, features a refreshed design, and supports giving separate wallpapers to each virtual desktop.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] When a display is disconnected in a multi-monitor configuration, the windows that were previously on that display will be minimized rather than automatically moved to the main display.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] If the same display is reconnected, the windows are restored to their prior location.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In June 2025, Microsoft unveiled *Xbox mode*, a new interface designed primarily for handheld gaming PCs; similarly to SteamOS, it boots directly into the Xbox app and bypasses the Windows desktop entirely, reducing resource consumption and providing a more console-like interface.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The task switcher and lock screen also have optimizations for gamepad input.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The new mode was a timed exclusive to the ROG Xbox Ally, and become generally available in April 2026 in selected territories.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] On October 21, 2021, Windows Subsystem for Android (WSA) became available to Beta channel builds of Windows 11 for users in the United States, which allowed users to install and run Android apps on their devices.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Users could install Android apps through any source using the APK file format.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] An Amazon Appstore client for Microsoft Store was also available.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The Windows Subsystem for Android and Amazon Appstore became available to Release channel users in the United States on February 15, 2022, in Windows 11 Release build 22000.527.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] On March 5, 2024, Microsoft announced deprecation of WSA with support ending on March 5, 2025.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] WSA was based on the Intel Bridge runtime compiler; Intel stated that the technology was not dependent on its CPUs, and would also be supported on x86-64 and ARM CPUs from other vendors.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Home and Pro (since version 22H2) edition installation requires internet connection and Microsoft account login (only if for personal use on Pro) is mandatory unless manually bypassed to create a local user.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] However, Microsoft has since blocked one of the last remaining easy bypass methods that allowed local account creation during initial setup, complicating the bypass process further.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] All other editions are excluded from this requirement.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] As part of the minimum system requirements, Windows 11 only runs on devices with a Trusted Platform Module 2.0 security coprocessor, albeit with some exceptions, see § System requirements for details.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] According to Microsoft, the TPM 2.0 coprocessor is a "critical building block" for protection against firmware and hardware attacks.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In addition, Microsoft now requires devices with Windows 11 to include virtualization-based security (VBS), hypervisor-protected code integrity (HVCI), and Secure Boot built-in and enabled by default.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The operating system also features hardware-enforced stack protection for supported Intel and AMD processors for protection against zero-day exploits.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Like its predecessor, Windows 11 also supports multi-factor authentication and biometric authentication through Windows Hello.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In subsequent updates, Microsoft added several features based on artificial intelligence (AI), like live captions, background noise removal in videoconferencing, webcam auto-framing that follows the user's movements, and AI-powered Bing Chat in the taskbar's search field.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Following the integration of GPT-4 in Microsoft's other products, the company announced that by summer 2023, the newly released Microsoft Copilot would add GPT-4 integration to the Windows taskbar.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] On May 20, 2024, Microsoft officially announced Recall, a feature that uses a hardware AI accelerator to locally store snapshots of the user's activity (including content transcribed using live captions), and which allows users to search through them.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] This feature is exclusive to devices certified under the "Copilot+ PC" branding.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Following concerns over the security implications of Recall, Microsoft announced in June 2024 that it would delay the release of the feature to allow for testing and feedback via the Windows Insider program.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In July 2025, Microsoft released Copilot Vision, a tool which scans a user's screen and uses Copilot to analyze the contents.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In March 2026, Microsoft indicated in a blog post that they would reduce "unnecessary" presence of Copilot in certain basic apps.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 is available in two main editions; the **Home** edition, which is intended for consumer users, and the **Pro** edition, which contains additional networking and security features (such as BitLocker), as well as the ability to join a domain.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 Home may be restricted by default to verified software obtained from Microsoft Store ("S Mode").
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 Home requires an Internet connection and a Microsoft account in order to complete first-time setup.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] This restriction is also applied to Windows 11 Pro since version 22H2 as it was announced in February 2022, although a Microsoft account is not required if it is not for personal use.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Other editions include Pro Education, Pro for Workstations, Education, Enterprise, Enterprise multi-session, IoT Enterprise, Enterprise LTSC, IoT Enterprise LTSC, Home Single Language, and Team; along with regional variations.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] These editions remain fundamentally the same as their Windows 10 edition counterparts.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Two new edition variants called IoT Enterprise Subscription and IoT Enterprise Subscription LTSC have been introduced in version 24H2.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] As with other versions of Windows since Windows XP, Microsoft has also distributed special editions of Windows 11 designated as "N" and "KN" to comply with the antitrust laws within the European Union and South Korea respectively.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] These editions removed the built-in Media Players but users have encouraged to download the third party media software; DirectX components such as DXVA and Media Foundation still reserved.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The 38 fully-localized Language Pack (LP) languages were available as both lp.cab and .appx packages, while the remaining 72 partially-localized Language Interface Pack (LIP) languages were only available as .appx packages.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] With Windows 11, that process has changed.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Five new LP languages were added — Catalan, Basque, Galician, Indonesian, and Vietnamese — bringing the total number of LP languages to 43.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Furthermore, these 43 languages can only be imaged using lp.cab packages.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] This is to ensure a fully supported language-imaging and cumulative update experience.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The remaining 67 LIP languages that are LXP-based will move to a self-service model, and can only be added by Windows users themselves via the Microsoft Store and Windows Settings apps, not during the Windows imaging process.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Like Windows 10, Windows 11 follows Microsoft's Modern Lifecycle Policy.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Each annual feature update has its own support lifecycle: two years for the Home and Pro editions, and three years for the Education and Enterprise editions.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Microsoft has stated that Windows 11 provides no lifecycle guarantee if it has been installed on a machine that does not meet its minimum hardware requirements.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 receives annual major updates, though Microsoft sometimes adds major features in mid-cycle releases.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Starting in 2022, in the Enterprise and Education editions, major features added in yearly releases will be turned off by default until the next yearly release, though these features can be manually enabled as a group policy.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Only available to devices with certain ARM processors.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Version 24H2, notably, has a longer than usual list of known issues.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Some require updated drivers or (free) software updates to fix, while others have yet to be fixed as of March 2025.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] E.g., broken biometrics and camera support on a limited number of devices, and some older games and applications not functioning properly or not working at all; e.g., *Asphalt 8* and Dirac audio improvement software (if cridspapo.dll is utilized).
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The basic system requirements of Windows 11 differ significantly from Windows 10.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 only supports 64-bit systems such as those using an x86-64 or ARM64 processor; IA-32 and ARM32 processors are no longer supported.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Thus, Windows 11 is the first consumer version of Windows without 32-bit processors (although Windows Server 2008 R2 is the first version of Windows Server without them).
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The minimum RAM and storage requirements were also increased; Windows 11 now requires at least 4 GB of RAM and 64 GB of storage.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Also for the first time, TPM 2.0 is now required, however, Original equipment manufacturers (OEM) can still ship computers without TPM 2.0 enabled upon Microsoft's approval.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] S mode is only supported for the Home edition of Windows 11.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In addition, for the first time, Microsoft enforces a processor model check before installation (although not on all editions, e.g., some IoT editions are excluded), where the processor model is checked against a Microsoft whitelist.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The Intel compatibility list also includes the Intel Core i7-7820HQ, a seventh-generation processor used by the Surface Studio 2, although only on devices that shipped with DCH-based drivers.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The processor compatibility lists Microsoft provides are cumulative, e.g., all processors listed as compatible with version 21H2 are also compatible with version 24H2.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] However, newer version lists (post version 21H2) may omit older processor models, as these lists are primarily intended for use by OEMs, for newly manufactured devices.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Regardless, as of February 2025, Microsoft now recommends that consumers simply ignore these lists and instead verify processor compatibility via the Microsoft PC Health Check app.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] This change was due to previous consumer confusion, initially perpetuated by erroneous reports from some news outlets.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] On May 20, 2024, Microsoft announced "Copilot+ PC"—a brand of Windows 11 devices that are designed to support enhanced artificial intelligence features.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Copilot+ PCs require an on-board AI accelerator, at least 256 GB of storage, and at least 16 GB of RAM.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The first wave of Copilot+ PCs run the Qualcomm Snapdragon X Elite system-on-chip. x86-64-based Copilot+ PCs began to be announced later in the year, which are based on AMD Ryzen AI and Intel Core Ultra CPUs.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Devices with unsupported 64-bit processors are not blocked from installing or running Windows 11; however, a clean install or upgrade using ISO installation media must be performed as Windows Update will not offer an upgrade from Windows 10.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Additionally, users must also accept an on-screen disclaimer stating that they will not be entitled to receive updates, and that damage caused by using Windows 11 on an unsupported configuration are not covered by the manufacturer's warranty.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] In addition, various unofficial methods to bypass other Windows 11 official requirements, such as, but not limited to, TPM 2.0 exist; furthermore there also exists an official bypass method provided directly by Microsoft (whereas the installation itself remains unofficially supported).
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Intel Core 2 (like the Core 2 Duo and Core 2 Quad), AMD K10 CPUs (such as Phenom II and Athlon II) and older are no longer supported.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Finally, version 24H2 now requires ARMv8.1, dropping unofficial support for ARMv8.0, e.g., the Snapdragon 835 and older are no longer supported.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Legacy BIOS is no longer officially supported; a UEFI system and a Trusted Platform Module (TPM) 2.0 security coprocessor is now officially required.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The TPM requirement in particular has led to confusion as many motherboards do not have TPM support, or require a compatible TPM to be physically installed onto the motherboard.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] ARM64 version of Windows 11 requires the UEFI firmware with ACPI protocol.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Starting with version 24H2, IoT Enterprise editions have officially reintroduced legacy BIOS support and eliminated the requirement for a TPM.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Some third-party software may refuse to run on configurations of Windows 11 that do not comply with the hardware security requirement.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] While IoT Enterprise editions have always had slightly reduced official requirements compared to other Windows 11 editions, notably starting with version 24H2, minimum requirements were further reduced and now differ significantly.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] These updated 24H2 requirements were announced on May 22, 2024, for both LTSC and non-LTSC editions.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] For the first time since Windows 11 release, Microsoft has officially eliminated a TPM and UEFI minimum requirement for all systems running these editions and dropped the minimum DirectX version down to 10 (version 12 was previously required on 23H2).
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Finally, the IoT Enterprise LTSC edition further drops the minimum required RAM to 2 GB and storage space to 16 GB.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Reception of Windows 11 upon its reveal was positive, with critics praising the new design and productivity features.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] However, Microsoft was criticized for creating confusion over the minimum system requirements for Windows 11.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The increased system requirements (compared to those of Windows 10) initially published by Microsoft meant that up to 60% of existing Windows 10 PCs were unable to upgrade to Windows 11, which has faced concerns that this will contribute to electronic waste.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Stephen Kleynhans, the Research Vice President of Gartner, an American research firm, felt that Microsoft was "looking at the entire stack from the hardware up through the applications and the user experience and trying to make the entire stack work better and more securely.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Andrew Cunningham of *Ars Technica* gave a mixed but overall cautiously positive review of Windows 11 upon its release.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] He praised the improvements to its visual design (describing the new "Mica" appearance as reminiscent of the visual appearance of iOS and macOS, and arguing that Microsoft had "[made] a serious effort" at making the user-facing aspects of Windows 11 more consistent visually.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] He also praised window management, performance (assessed as being equivalent to if not better than Windows 10), other "beneficial tweaks".
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Criticism was raised towards Widgets' lack of support for third-party content, thus limiting it to Microsoft services only, regressions in taskbar functionality and customization.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] He also noted the inability to easily select default applications for common tasks such as web browsing, as it requires the user to select the browser application for each file type individually.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Apart from the user interface, system requirements and Microsoft's unclear justification for its processor compatibility criteria remained a major sticking point for him.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] While some of the system requirements have brought greater public attention to hardware security features present on modern PCs, he argued that these could already be employed on Windows 10, albeit optionally.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Cunningham concluded that "as I've dug into [Windows 11] and learned its ins and outs for this review, I've warmed to it more", but argued that the OS was facing similar "public perception" issues to Windows Vista and Windows 8.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] However, he noted that 11 did not have as many performance issues or bugs as Vista had upon its release, nor was as "disjointed" as 8, and recommended that users who were unsure about the upgrade should stay on Windows 10 in anticipation of future updates to 11.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Warren noted that he rarely used the Widgets panel or Microsoft Teams, citing that he preferred the weather display that later versions of Windows 10 offered, and did not use Teams to communicate with his friends and family.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] He also acknowledged the expansion of the Microsoft Store to include more "traditional" desktop applications.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Overall, he concluded that "I wouldn't rush out to upgrade to Windows 11, but I also wouldn't avoid it.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] He concluded that Windows 11 "feels practical and productive, but less so than its predecessor in many aspects", while its best features were either "hidden deeper within", required specific hardware (DirectStorage, Auto HDR) or were not available on launch (Android app support).
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Critics have also noted that as of 2024, Windows 11 was slower for gaming than Windows 10.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Some games, such as *Cyberpunk 2077* and *A Plague Tale: Requiem*, ran 10% faster on Windows 10 than on Windows 11.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] This was a reversal of early profiling which suggested an advantage for Windows 11.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Adoption briefly overtook Windows 10 among Steam users in early 2025, only for this to be dramatically reversed that March with a 10% rise in Windows 10 users.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] This may be related to consumer changes in China.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The poor performance of Windows 11 for gaming has been highlighted as an issue for handheld gaming computers with the launch of the ROG Xbox Ally.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Valve's SteamOS performs faster, has a more cohesive interface, and a larger install base thanks to the success of the Steam Deck.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Notably, the ROG Ally consistently performs better if users replace Windows 11 with SteamOS.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The difference was more noticeable on the ROG Xbox Ally, where replacing Windows 11 with Bazzite can increase framerates by 32% for *Kingdom Come Deliverance 2*.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 was slow to be adopted, with Microsoft relying on "annoying" ads and pop-ups to convince Windows 10 users to upgrade.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Adoption remained slow until early 2025, ahead of the end-of-life for Windows 10.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Windows 11 did not overtake Windows 10's market share until July 2025, approximately four years after launch and only three months before Windows 10's end-of-life.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The shift in mid 2025 was largely driven by enterprise upgrades rather than individual consumers.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] As of July 2025, Windows 11 stood at 50.24% share.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] The hardware requirements for Windows 11, and the large number of incompatible devices still in use meant that there was also an increase in Linux use over the period, reaching 5% of desktop market share.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] Adoption among PC gamers was similarly slow, but on balance faster than with other kinds of users.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] According to Valve Corporation's hardware and software survey, the market-share of Windows 11 among the user-base of Steam (the leading digital distribution platform for computer games) started overtaking that of Windows 10 by August 2024.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-android] As of September 2025, a month ahead of Windows 10's end-of-life, Windows 11's share among Steam users sits at 66 percent of Windows systems, and 63 percent of all systems.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] The original version, WSL 1, differs significantly from the second major version, WSL 2.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL 1 (released August 2, 2016), acted as a compatibility layer for running Linux binary executables (in ELF format) by implementing Linux system calls in the Windows kernel.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL 2 (announced May 2019), introduced a real Linux kernel – a managed virtual machine (via Hyper-V) that implements the full Linux kernel.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] As a result, WSL 2 is compatible with more Linux binaries as not all system calls were implemented in WSL 1.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] As of June 2026, WSL 1 is still maintained and supported.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Microsoft offers WSL for a variety of reasons.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Microsoft envisions WSL as "a tool for developers – especially web developers and those who work on or with open source projects".
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Microsoft also claims that "WSL requires fewer resources (CPU, memory, and storage) than a full virtual machine" (a common alternative for using Linux in Windows), while also allowing the use of both Windows and Linux tools on the same set of files.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] The majority of WSL was released as open source software on May 19, 2025, although certain filesystem functions still rely on a closed-source proprietary library as of September 2025.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Microsoft's first foray into achieving Unix-like compatibility on Windows was the Microsoft POSIX subsystem, superseded by Windows Services for UNIX via MKS/Interix, which was eventually deprecated with the release of Windows 8.1.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] The technology behind Windows Subsystem for Linux originated in the unreleased Project Astoria, which enabled some Android applications to run on Windows 10 Mobile.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] It was first made available in Windows 10 Insider Preview build 14316.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Whereas Microsoft's prior projects and the third-party Cygwin had focused on creating their own unique Unix-like environments based on the POSIX standard, WSL aimed for native Linux compatibility.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL beta was introduced in Windows 10 version 1607 (Anniversary Update) on August 2, 2016.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Only Ubuntu (with Bash as the default shell) was supported.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL beta was also called "Bash on Ubuntu on Windows" or "Bash on Windows".
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL was no longer beta in Windows 10 version 1709 (Fall Creators Update), released on October 17, 2017.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Multiple Linux distributions could be installed and were available for install in the Windows Store.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] At a Microsoft Ignite conference in 2018, Microsoft engineers gave a high-level overview of a new "lightweight" Hyper-V VM technology for containerization where a virtualized kernel could make direct use of NT primitives on the host.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] In 2019, Microsoft announced a completely redesigned WSL architecture (WSL 2) using this lightweight VM technology hosting actual (customized) Linux kernel images, claiming to provide full syscall compatibility.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Microsoft announced WSL 2 on May 6, 2019, and it was shipped with Windows 10 version 2004.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] It was also backported to Windows 10 version 1903 and 1909.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] GPU support for WSL 2 to run GPU-accelerated machine learning was introduced in Windows build 20150.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] GUI support for WSL 2 to run Linux applications with graphical user interfaces (GUIs) was introduced in Windows build 21364.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] In April 2021, Microsoft released a Windows 10 test build that also includes the ability to run Linux graphical user interface (GUI) apps using WSL 2 and CBL-Mariner.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] The Windows Subsystem for Linux GUI (WSLg) was officially released at the Microsoft Build 2021 conference.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] It is included in Windows 10 Insider build 21364 or later.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] On October 11, 2021, Microsoft introduced a version of WSL in the Microsoft Store for Windows 11.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] It reached version 1.0.0 in November 2022 with added support for Windows 10.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] In November 2024, Microsoft announced new features coming to WSL intended to improve the experience for new users, including a window with new "getting started" navigation tips and explanations.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] On May 19, 2025, during Build, Microsoft announced that the majority of WSL had been released as open source software, aside from a driver used by WSL 1, and the IFS network redirector drivers on WSL 2.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] The first release of WSL provides a Linux-compatible kernel interface developed by Microsoft, containing no Linux kernel code, which can then run the user space of a Linux distribution on it, such as Ubuntu, openSUSE, SUSE Linux Enterprise Server, Fedora, CentOS, AlmaLinux, Debian, and Kali Linux.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Such a user space might contain a GNU Bash shell and command language, with native GNU command-line tools (sed, awk, etc.), programming-language interpreters (Ruby, Python, etc.), and even graphical applications (using an X11 server at the host side).
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] The architecture was redesigned in WSL 2, with a Linux kernel running in a lightweight virtual machine environment.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] The `wsl.exe` command accesses and manages Linux distributions in WSL via command-line interface (CLI) – for example via Command Prompt or PowerShell.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] With no arguments it enters the default distribution shell.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] It can list available distributions, set a default distribution, and uninstall distributions.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] It can also run a Linux command – replacing `lxrun.exe` which is deprecated as of Windows 10 1803 and later.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Windows Subsystem for Linux GUI (WSLg) is built with the purpose of enabling support for running graphical X11 and Wayland applications on Windows in a fully integrated desktop experience.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSLg was officially released at the Microsoft Build 2021 conference and is included in Windows 10 Insider build 21364 or later.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] However, with the introduction of Windows 11, WSLg is finally shipping with a production build of Windows, bringing support for both graphics and audio in WSL apps.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] FreeRDP is used to encode all communications going from the Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) Server (in Weston) to the RDP Client (msrdc on Windows) according to the RDP protocol specifications.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] All processes invoked by a particular user go into a so called "Linux Instance" (usually the first invoked process is init).
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Once all the applications are closed, the instance is closed.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL 1's design featured no hardware emulation / virtualization (unlike other projects such as coLinux) and made direct use of the host file system (through `VolFS` and `DrvFS`) and some parts of the hardware, such as the network, which guarantees interoperability.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Web servers for example, can be accessed through the same interfaces and IP addresses configured on the host, and shares the same restrictions on the use of ports that require administrative permissions, or ports already occupied by other applications.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] There are certain locations (such as system folders) and configurations whose access/modification is restricted, even when running as root, with sudo from the shell.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] An instance with elevated privileges must be launched in order to get "sudo" to give administrator privileges, and allow such access.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL 1 is not capable of running all Linux software, such as 32-bit binaries, or those that require specific Linux kernel services not implemented in WSL.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Due to a total lack of Linux in WSL 1, kernel modules, such as device drivers, cannot be run.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL 2, however, makes use of live virtualized Linux kernel instances.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Support for OpenCL and CUDA is also not being implemented currently, although planned for future releases.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Microsoft stated WSL was designed for the development of applications, and not for desktop computers or production servers, recommending the use of virtual machines (Hyper-V), Kubernetes, and Azure for those purposes.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] In benchmarks, WSL 1's performance is often near native Linux Ubuntu, Debian, Intel Clear Linux or other Linux distributions.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] I/O is in some tests a bottleneck for WSL.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] The redesigned WSL 2 backend is claimed by Microsoft to offer twenty-fold increases in speed on certain operations compared to that of WSL 1.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] In June 2020, a benchmark with 173 tests on WSL 2 (20H2) with an AMD Ryzen Threadripper 3970X showed an average of 87% of the performance of native Ubuntu 20.04 LTS.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] In contrast, WSL 1 had only 70% of the performance of native Ubuntu.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL 2 improves I/O performance, providing a near-native level.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] A comparison of 69 tests with an Intel Core i9-10900K in May 2020 resulted in nearly the same relative performance.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] In December 2020, a benchmark with 43 tests on WSL 2 (20H2) with an AMD Ryzen 9 5900X displayed an average of 93% of the performance of native 20.04.1 LTS, compared to WSL 1 which only achieved 73%.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Version 2 introduces changes in the architecture.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Microsoft has opted for virtualization through a highly optimized subset of Hyper-V features, in order to run the kernel and distributions (based upon the kernel), promising performance equivalent to WSL 1.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] For backward compatibility, developers do not need to change anything in their published distributions.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL 2 settings can be tweaked by the *WSL global configuration*, contained in an INI file named `.wslconfig` in the User Profile folder.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] The distribution installation resides inside an ext4-formatted filesystem inside a virtual disk, and the host file system is transparently accessible through the 9P protocol, similarly to other virtual machine technologies like QEMU.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] For the users, Microsoft promised up to 20 times the read/write performance of WSL 1.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] From Windows an IFS network redirector is provided for Linux guest file access using the UNC path prefix of `\\wsl$`.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL 2 requires Windows 11, or Windows 10 version 1903 or higher, with Build 18362 or higher, for x64 systems, and Version 2004 or higher, with Build 19041 or higher, for ARM64 systems.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL 2 on Windows 11 retains 95% of the performance of native Ubuntu 20.04 LTS.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL 1 and WSL 2 both support IPv6 connections.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] IPv6 support in WSL 2 requires Windows 11 or newer.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] In 2021, Jim Salter writing for *Ars Technica* called WSL "the best part of Windows 11," noting the ability to run applications with graphics and sound and install multiple distributions side-by-side.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] WSL has most widely been described as a tool more useful to developers, rather than end users.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-subsystem-for-linux] Reviewers criticized some limitations, noting that it is not the same as having Linux, and that it suffers from some performance limitations, including slow disk I/O.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-terminal] Since Windows 11 22H2 and Windows Terminal 1.15, Windows Terminal replaces Windows Console as the default.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-terminal] Windows Terminal was announced at Microsoft's Build 2019 developer conference in May 2019 as a modern alternative for Windows Console, and Windows Terminal's source code first appeared on GitHub on May 3, 2019.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-terminal] The first preview release was version 0.2, which appeared on July 10, 2019.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-terminal] The first stable version of the project (version 1.0) was on May 19, 2020, at which point, Microsoft started releasing preview versions as the Windows Terminal Preview app, which could be installed side-by-side with the stable version.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-terminal] It can run multiple command-line apps, including text-based shells in a multi-tabbed window.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-terminal] It has out-of-the-box support for Command Prompt, PowerShell, and Bash on Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL).
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-terminal] It can natively connect to Azure Cloud Shell.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-terminal] Cascadia Code is a purpose-built monospaced font by Aaron Bell of Saja Typeworks for the new command-line interface.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-terminal] It includes programming ligatures and was designed to enhance the look and feel of Windows Terminal, terminal applications and text editors such as Visual Studio and Visual Studio Code.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-terminal] The font is open-source under the SIL Open Font License and available on GitHub.
[src:wsl-subsystem/windows-terminal] It is bundled with Windows Terminal since version 0.5.2762.0.
